    "updated_at": "2025-06-26T16:04:09Z",
    "body": "Starship also doesn't export `VIRTUAL_ENV_DISABLE_PROMPT`, it merely sets it within the current shell's environment. starship is triggered in `.zshrc` or `.bashrc`; however, VS Code will detect environment variables by executing a non-login shell, which only sources `.zprofile` or `.bash_profile` respectively. If you're using a Python virtual environment, VS code will spawn the shell with the virtual environment sourced before your profile but will include any environment variables discovered ahead of time. `VIRTUAL_ENV_DISABLE_PROMPT` only takes effect at the time the virtual env profile is sourced. Setting it afterwards has no effect.\n\nIt's a bit of a mess. But, what this means is that if you put `export VIRTUAL_ENV_DISABLE_PROMPT=1` in your `.zprofile` or `.bash_profile`, then this problem goes away. This should apply to all other shells as well as most have a concept of a profile for non-login and a rc for login environments.",
